I know the palindromes are cheating. $n = r(n)$ means $n - r(n) = 0$, which is $0^2$, a perfect square by definition. So any palindrome $n$ where $n + r(n) = 2n$ is a square is balanced. That’s why $2k^2$ palindromes are infinite and trivial. We agreed to shut that door. We need $n \neq r(n)$. We need $B > 0$.

Let’s look at the structure again. Let $n + r(n) = A^2$ and $n - r(n) = B^2$.
Adding them gives $2n = A^2 + B^2$.
Subtracting them gives $2r(n) = A^2 - B^2$.

This is elegant. $n$ is half the sum of two squares, and $r(n)$ is half the difference of those same two squares.
Also, $A$ and $B$ must have the same parity because $A^2 + B^2 = 2n$ is even. If both are odd, $A^2 \equiv 1 \pmod 4$ and $B^2 \equiv 1 \pmod 4$, so $A^2 - B^2$ is divisible by 8
